				\begin{document}$$\varepsilon (x,t)={{\rm{T}}}_{\varepsilon 1}(x,t)\times {{\rm{T}}}_{\varepsilon 2}(x,t)\times {{\rm{W}}}_{\varepsilon }(x,t)\times {\varepsilon }_{{\rm{\max }}}$$\end{document}ε(x,t)=Tε1(x,t)×Tε2(x,t)×Wε(x,t)×εmaxwhere Tε1(x, t) and Tε2(x, t) denote the temperature stress coefficients on light use efficiency, Wε(x, t) is the water stress coefficient that indicates the reduction in light use efficiency caused by moisture, and εmax denotes the maximum light use efficiency under ideal conditions set as the maximum possible light energy conversion efficiency. As for the vegetation in China, it may not be the same as global vegetation parameters43; hence, we use the parameters for grassland maximum light use efficiency in China as simulated by Zhu et al.44 and this term is set uniformly at 0.542 g C MJ−1 for grassland in Xinjiang. A more detailed description of algorithm for Wε(x, t) calculation and improvement can be found in Zhu et al.44.

We detect long term annual NPP trend changes in every pixel by linear regression analysis. Existing research shows that the Greenness Rate of Change (GRC) can reflect the change trend of grassland NPP within a certain period of time45, following the equation (8):8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
